docs.abstract: European antitrust regulators have opened an investigation into the data that Amazon uses from third-party sellers who rely on the tech company’s site
docs.snippet: European antitrust regulators have opened an investigation into the data that Amazon uses from third-party sellers who rely on the tech company’s site
docs.lead_paragraph: LONDON — Amazon faces a widening inquiry in Europe over whether it unfairly uses data collected from third-party sellers who rely on its platform, the latest move by regulators around the world to curb the growing power of big technology companies.

headline.main: Amazon Faces E.U. Inquiry Over Data From Independent Sellers
headline.print_headline: Amazon Is Facing An Antitrust Inquiry By E.U. Regulators

docs.abstract: The international tax system is behind the times. But we need coordinated reform.
docs.snippet: The international tax system is behind the times. But we need coordinated reform.
docs.lead_paragraph: Last Thursday, the French Senate passed a digital services tax, which would impose an entirely new tax on large multinationals that provide digital services to consumers or users in France.

headline.main: Beware. Other Nations Will Follow France With Their Own Digital Tax.
headline.print_headline: Digital Services Will Be Taxed, but How?

docs.abstract: A wide range of companies are lining up to complain about Silicon Valley’s power as lawmakers and regulators step up their scrutiny of Big Tech.
docs.snippet: A wide range of companies are lining up to complain about Silicon Valley’s power as lawmakers and regulators step up their scrutiny of Big Tech.
docs.lead_paragraph: SAN FRANCISCO — Oracle and the Handpulled Noodle would seem to have little in common. One is a multibillion-dollar software company in Silicon Valley with tens of thousands of employees all over the world. The other is a small Harlem spot that serves Chinese comfort food and is known for its tasty dumplings.

headline.main: Anger at Big Tech Unites Noodle Pullers and Code Writers
headline.print_headline: Smaller Rivals  Aim Slingshots At Tech Giants

byline.original: By Jack Nicas and Karen Weise

docs.abstract: For decades, antitrust regulation has focused on the welfare of the consumer. Now a backlash over Big Tech’s power has regulators and scholars trying to reverse years of established doctrine.
docs.snippet: For decades, antitrust regulation has focused on the welfare of the consumer. Now a backlash over Big Tech’s power has regulators and scholars trying to reverse years of established doctrine.
docs.lead_paragraph: SAN FRANCISCO — When Americans fear the future, they turn to antitrust action.

headline.main: To Take Down Big Tech, They First Need to Reinvent the Law
headline.print_headline: Antitrust Regulators Size Up Tech Giants

docs.abstract: Ms. Warren seeks to break up companies like Amazon, Google, Apple and Facebook. And she has taken her fight to Silicon Valley.
docs.snippet: Ms. Warren seeks to break up companies like Amazon, Google, Apple and Facebook. And she has taken her fight to Silicon Valley.
docs.lead_paragraph: Senator Elizabeth Warren of Massachusetts believes that the government must break up monopolies and promote competitive markets. That’s why she has taken aim at America’s largest tech companies.

headline.main: Elizabeth Warren on Breaking Up Big Tech

docs.abstract: The streaming wars are heating up and the phone giant’s new service will have “Friends” exclusively.
docs.snippet: The streaming wars are heating up and the phone giant’s new service will have “Friends” exclusively.
docs.lead_paragraph: After AT&T spent over $80 billion to acquire Time Warner in part to take on Netflix, the phone giant’s new streaming service finally has a name: HBO Max. The company also announced it will debut next spring and will offer 10,000 hours of content, including exclusive access to the hit show “Friends.”

headline.main: ‘Friends’ to Leave Netflix for HBO Max, AT&T’s New Streaming Service

docs.abstract: They bet on properties as diverse as office buildings, warehouses, data centers and timberlands. And they’ve been outperforming the stock market.
docs.snippet: They bet on properties as diverse as office buildings, warehouses, data centers and timberlands. And they’ve been outperforming the stock market.
docs.lead_paragraph: After years of being overshadowed by the likes of Apple and Alphabet, real estate funds have lately edged ahead of the overall stock market by betting mainly on old-fashioned assets like office buildings, malls and warehouses.

headline.main: Real Estate Funds Have Been a Balm in a Stinging Market
headline.print_headline: Stodgy Real Estate Funds Get Another Look

docs.abstract: John Herrman, who writes about the internet, is using many of the same tech tools as a decade ago — but the conversation around how we use them has changed.
docs.snippet: John Herrman, who writes about the internet, is using many of the same tech tools as a decade ago — but the conversation around how we use them has changed.
docs.lead_paragraph: How do New York Times journalists use technology in their jobs and in their personal lives? John Herrman, a reporter for the Styles desk who covers the internet, discussed the tech he’s using.

headline.main: The Tools for Covering Tech Are the Same as in 2009
headline.print_headline: Untangling the Internet the Old-Fashioned Way
